{"title_page": "El Capo", "text_new": "{{about|the Colombian TV series|other uses|Capo (disambiguation)}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2009}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = El Capo(A.K.A. el capo Dzony\n| image     = \n| caption   = \n| director  = {{unbulleted list|[[Riccardo Gabrielli R.]]|[[Lilo Vilaplana]]}}\n| producer  = {{unbulleted list|Amparo Lopez|Nelson Martinez|[[Jorge Sastoque Roa]]}}\n| writer    = [[Gustavo Bol\u00edvar M.]]\n| starring  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Marlon Moreno]]\n* [[Katherine Velez]]\n* [[Marcela Mar]]\n* [[Maria Adelaida Puerta]]\n* [[Diego Trujillo]]\n* [[Natalia Jerez]]\n* [[Elkin Diaz]]\n* [[Oscar Borda]]\n* [[Manuel Sarmiento]]\n}}\n| network   = {{unbulleted list|[[RCN Televisi\u00f3n]] (2009\u20132010)|[[MundoFox]] (2012\u20132014)}}\n}}\n\n'''''Marlon Moreno El Capo''''', commonly known as '''''El Capo''''', is a [[television series]] made by [[Fox Telecolombia]] and written by Gustavo Bolivar for [[RCN Television]], based on its namesake book.\n\nThe series follows the story of the fictional drug lord Pedro Pablo Le\u00f3n Jaramillo, a man who by necessity, chance and ambition has become the richest and most wanted drug trafficker in Colombia.  Despite his immense wealth, Pedro Pablo has maintained a low profile over the course of his life and has kept his role as a drug cartel leader a secret from his friends and family.  This strategy has allowed him to fly under the radar of the authorities for years, but has also inadvertently created a complex web of betrayals, loves and hates that grows beyond his control. As the truth is revealed, Pedro Pablo's world begins falling apart around him.\n\nThe series aired in the [[United States]] from 2009-2014, with the first season (2009-10) airing on the [[TeleFutura]] network, and the last two seasons (2012-14) airing on [[MundoFox]].\n\n== Cast ==\n=== Main cast ===\n<!-- NOTE; READ THIS NOTE: Per Wikipedia:WikiProject Television/Style guidelines#Cast information, \"The cast should be organized according to the series original broadcast credits, with new cast members being added to the end of the list. Please keep in mind that 'main' cast status is determined by the series producers, not by popularity or screen time. Furthermore, articles should reflect the entire history of a series, and as such actors remain on the list even after their departure from the series.\" NOTE; READ THE ABOVE NOTE. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 scope=\"col\" | Actor\n! rowspan=2 scope=\"col\" | Character\n! colspan=4 | Season\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| 1\n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| 2\n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Marlon Moreno\n| Pedro Pablo Le\u00f3n Jaramillo\n| colspan=3 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Marcela Mar]]\n| Marcela Li\u00e9vano\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mar\u00eda Adelaida Puerta\n| Pilar Monroy \"La Perrys\"\n| colspan=2 {{CMain}} \n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Katherine V\u00e9lez\n| Isabel Cristina\n| colspan=3 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Cristina Uma\u00f1a]]\n| Bruna\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=2 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Carolina Ram\u00edrez\n| Mariele\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u00d3scar Borda\n| Osvaldo Tovar \"Tato\"\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Roberto Cano\n| El Burro\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Daniel Lugo (actor)|Daniel Lugo]]\n| Pac\u00edfico Blanco\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Juan Carlos Vargas\n| Detective Velandia\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Natalia Jerez\n| Juliana Le\u00f3n Marin\n| colspan=2 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Alfonso Herrera]]\n| Juan Vicente Blanco \"Ni\u00f1o Malo\"\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Michelle Manterola\n| Kyara\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Manuel Navarro\n| Jacob Bauman\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Juan Alfonso Baptista]]\n| Pitre\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Rub\u00e9n Zamora\n| Braulio\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Marcelo Dos Santos\n| Terry Bianchini\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Alberto Pujol\n| Uriel Valenciano\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{CMain}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Recurring cast ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 scope=\"col\" | Actor\n! rowspan=2 scope=\"col\" | Character\n! colspan=4 | Season\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| 1\n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| 2\n! style=\"width:15%;\" scope=\"col\"| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Diego Trujillo]]\n| Guillermo Holguin\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Manuel Sarmiento\n| Chemo\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Elkin D\u00edaz\n| Hern\u00e1n Le\u00f3n Jaramillo \"Nancho\"\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Manuel Jos\u00e9 Ch\u00e1vez\n| Juan Pablo Le\u00f3n Mar\u00edn\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mar\u00eda Cristina Pimiento\n| Alejandra Pineda\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Florina Lemaitre\n| Ofelia\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Felipe Calero\n| Felipe Holguin\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Herbert King (actor)|Herbert King]]\n| Coronel Gaviria\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Didier van der Hove]]\n|Pavel Asimov\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Guillermo Olarte\n| General Moncada\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ricardo Saldarriaga\n| General Sarmiento\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Calero\n|Fiscal Armando Grisales\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | H\u00e9ctor Garc\u00eda\n|Aristobulo Vanegas \"Federico Bar\u00f3n Correa\"\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=2 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Salvador del Solar\n|Rub\u00e9n Castro\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n| colspan=1 {{cRecurring}}\n| colspan=1 {{N/a|}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Plot ==\nIn his hidden underground bunker, Pedro Pablo (El Capo), his wife Isabel Cristina, his lover Marcela, and four of his men \u2013 his brother Nancho, Chemo, Perrys, and Tato, are hiding to escape the army. A cell phone brought in by Cristina receives a phone call, which is intercepted by a military spy plane, which is transmitted to a large military force encamped outside the bunker.\n\nWhen the military discovers something very rare in the lake, they drop two bombs on the lake to scare the wildlife out of the area. The detonations also damage the bunker, causing it to be evacuated of all but Tato, who is injured and left behind. While El Capo and the rest move to a nearby farm, Tato is captured. When the group makes it to the city, Nancho persuades a terminally ill AIDS man, named El Moro, to drive a car bomb to the Senate in exchange for 200 million pesos for his family. Nancho fails to tell Juan Carlos, El Capo's son, about the bomb, who is killed in the explosion. El Moro's children are rescued from the explosion by Perrys and Chemo, who pledge to take care of them. They then enlist a nurse and help Tato escape from the hospital prior to his being transported to jail. \n\nEl Capo has Juan Carlos' body stolen from the morgue, and brought to a series of caves they are hiding out in.  However, an informer has given their location to the military, who follow them there. It is revealed that General Moncado and General Sarmiento, who were with the military are actually allied with El Capo. They escape into the caves and join El Capo's men.  The military attacks the caves, and in the battle Chemo is killed. However, Moncada, Sarmiento and Perrys escape after the raid, with Perrys vowing to take care of El Moro's kids on her own. The military force is ramped up by the President, who is running for re-election. \n\nEl Capo and his band surrender, in order to protect the rest of his family. While in custody, several of the group are targeted for assassination, including Perrys and the nurse who helped Tato escape. When the President reneges on promises made to El Capo in exchange for his surrender, El Capo escapes with Nancho.  But in the ensuing chase, their car explodes, killing Nancho. Everyone also thinks that El Capo has died in the explosion. When she hears of his supposed death, El Capo's mother dies from grief. At his funeral, the police arrest Isabel Cristina and Marcella, but Tato and Perrys escape. After their escape, Perrys does not want to go with Tato, preferring to leave their life of crime and focus on raising her children. El Capo and Tato escape in a stolen car.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2018}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|name=''El Capo'' official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|title=El Capo}}\n* {{TheTVDB|title=El Capo}}\n\n{{RCN Telenovelas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capo}}\n[[Category:2009 Colombian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010 Colombian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2009 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Colombian telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Colombian crime television series]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language telenovelas]]\n[[Category:MundoMax original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Colombia]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Colombian TV series|other uses|Capo (disam