ado and General Sarmiento, who were with the military are actually allied with El Capo. They escape into the caves and join El Capo's men.  The military attacks the caves, and in the battle Chemo is killed. However, Moncada, Sarmiento and Perrys escape after the raid, with Perrys vowing to take care of El Moro's kids on her own. The military force is ramped up by the President, who is running for re-election. \n\nEl Capo and his band surrender, in order to protect the rest of his family. While in custody, several of the group are targeted for assassination, including Perrys and the nurse who helped Tato escape. When the President reneges on promises made to El Capo in exchange for his surrender, El Capo escapes with Nancho.  But in the ensuing chase, their car explodes, killing Nancho. Everyone also thinks that El Capo has died in the explosion. When she hears of his supposed death, El Capo's mother dies from grief. At his funeral, the police arrest Isabel Cristina and Marcella, but Tato and Perrys escape. After their escape, Perrys does not want to go with Tato, preferring to leave their life of crime and focus on raising her children. El Capo and Tato escape in a stolen car.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2018}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|name=''El Capo'' official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|title=El Capo}}\n* {{TheTVDB|title=El Capo}}\n\n{{RCN Telenovelas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capo}}\n[[Category:2009 Colombian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010 Colombian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2009 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Colombian telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Colombian crime television series]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language telenovelas]]\n[[Category:MundoMax original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Colombia]]\n", "name_user": "81.92.252.196", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Capo"}
{"title_page": "Shopping in Delhi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{advert|date=February 2018}}\n\nDelhi has been, since historical times, remained a favoured destination for shoppers. From traditional bazaars to modern-day swanky malls, Delhi has everything to offer to a customer. Delhi's street markets are reported to provide a greater turnover as compared to malls.<ref name=street>{{cite news|title=How Delhi's street markets clock Rs 20-30 lakh turnover|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/slideshows/biz-entrepreneurship/how-delhis-street-markets-clock-rs-20-30-lakh-turnover/overwhelming-variety/slideshow/20408211.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times | date=3 June 2013 | accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref> Since not everyone can afford to shop at malls or branded stores, most residents swear by the street markets. The quality of goods varies from market to market.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Delhi's street markets clock Rs 20-30 lakh turnover|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/slideshows/biz-entrepreneurship/how-delhis-street-markets-clock-rs-20-30-lakh-turnover/most-residents-swear-by-these-markets/slideshow/20408197.cms|website=indiatimes.com|publisher=Times Internet Limited|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nBelow is a list of famous shopping markets and malls in and around [[Delhi]].\n\n==Retail markets==\n* [[Connaught Place, New Delhi|Connaught Place]],<ref name=gov.in>{{cite web|title=Shopping in Delhi|url=http://www.delhitourism.gov.in/delhitourism/shopping/index.jsp|website=delhitourism.gov.in/|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> including [[Janpath]] and [[Palika Bazaar]].\n* [[Chandni Chowk]]<ref name=gov.in/> - A market running since the 17th century.<ref name=andrea/>\n* [[Karol Bagh]]<ref name=gov.in/>\n* [[Paharganj]]\n* [[Sarojini Nagar]]<ref name=gov.in/>\n* [[Khan Market]]<ref name=gov.in/><ref name=andrea/> - Most expensive retail location in India, in terms of per sq feet rental.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delhi's Khan Market is India's most expensive retail location|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-11-19/news/56265351_1_khan-market-expensive-retail-location-causeway-bay|accessdate=15 May 2015|agency=PTI|publisher=The Economic Times|date=19 November 2014|location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n* [[Lajpat Nagar]]\n* [[Dilli Haat]], INA and Pitampura - Government-run emporiums showcasing a rotating cast of regional artists and their crafts, such as bamboo & cane jewelry, handcarved wooden articles and papier-mache animals.<ref name=andrea>{{cite news|last1=Sachs|first1=Andrea|title=In India, surrendering to Delhi\u2019s market madness|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/travel/in-india-surrendering-to-delhis-market-madness/2015/04/30/15ff52c2-d1a5-11e4-ab77-9646eea6a4c7_story.html|accessdate=15 May 2015|publisher=Washington Post|date=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Hauz Khas]] Village Market,<ref name=gov.in/><ref>{{cite web|title=Hauz Khas Village|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/india/delhi/shopping/arts-crafts/hauz-khas-village|website=lonelyplanet.com|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> \n* [[South Extension]]\n* [[Nehru Place]]\n* [[Daryaganj]]\n* [[Gandhi Nagar, Delhi|Gandhi Nagar]]\n* [[Rajouri Garden]]\n* [[Tilak Nagar (Delhi)|Tilak Nagar]] Central Market\n* [[Rani Bagh, Delhi|Rani Bagh]]\n* [[Kohat Pitampura]]\n* [[Kamla Nagar]]\n\n==Wholesale markets==\n* [[Gandhi Nagar, Delhi|Delhi]]\n* [[Okhla|Okhla Mandi]]\n* [[Mehrauli]]\n* [[Chandni Chowk]]\n* [[Khari Baoli]]\n* [[List of clock towers|Ghanta Ghar]]\n* [[Bhajanpura]]\n\n==Shopping malls==\n\n===Delhi===\n*[[Ansal Plaza]], Hudco Place\n*[[Shivaji Place District Centre#Shopping Malls|West Gate Mall]]\n*[[Select Citywalk]], Saket\n\n===Noida===\n* [[DLF Mall of India]]\n* [[The Grand Venice Mall]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of shopping malls in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Delhi}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of Delhi]]\n[[Category:Retail markets in India]]\n[[Category:Retail mar